pularity was increased by the fame of the troubadour Bertrand de Born (<i>c.</i> 1140–1214). The name was taken to England by the Normans in the forms <i>Bertran(d)</i>, <i>Bertram</i>, and <i>Bartram</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Beltrami","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Dante, Dino, Marco, Pio, Sal, Tullio.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of the personal name <i>Beltrame</i>, from an ancient Germanic name composed of the elements <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’ + <i>hramn</i> ‘raven’. See also   Bertram  ."]},{"name":"Bartram","meanings":["English (of Norman origin) and North German: variant of   Bertram  .","History: William Bartram, a Quaker, had a large farm near Darby, PA, when his eldest son, John, the first American botanist, was born in 1699. John conducted botanical experiments at his own farm in Kingsessing, PA, near Philadelphia."]},{"name":"Bertman","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Frieda, Wilhelm.","Americanized form of German <b>Bertmann</b>: altered form (by folk etymology) of   Bertram  ."]},{"name":"Bethke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Eldor, Ewald, Otto, Rudi, Wilhelmina.","North German: from a pet form of the ancient Germanic personal names   Bertram   or   Berthold  . See also   Beth  ."]},{"name":"Bertrand","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Andre, Armand, Monique, Francois, Gilles, Raoul, Emile, Herve, Jacques, Jean-Marie, Odette.","French, Walloon, and West Indian (mainly Haiti): from the French personal name <i>Bertrand</i>, a variant of   Bertram  , coined by folk etymology under the influence of the present participle endings <i>-and</i>, <i>-ant</i>.","History: This surname is listed in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors and also in the similar register of the Huguenot Society of America."]},{"name":"Beltran","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Manuel, Carlos, Jesus, Luis, Pedro, Jorge, Mario, Ricardo, Francisco, Rafael.","Spanish (<b>Beltrán</b>), Catalan, and southern French: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’ + <i>hramn</i> ‘raven’. See also   Bertram  ."]},{"name":"Beltramo","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo.","Italian: from the medieval personal name <i>Beltramo</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see   Bertram  )."]},{"name":"Bert","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Philibert, Pierre.","German, French, and Polish: from a short form of various compound personal names formed with ancient Germanic <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’ (see for example   Bertram  ).","English: from the Middle English female personal name <i>Berte</i> (Old French <i>Berte</i>, from ancient Germanic   Berta  )."]},{"name":"Battermann","meanings":["German:","possibly an occupational name for a merchant or peddler, from <i>Bartermann</i>.","alternatively, perhaps from a short form of the personal name   Bertram   + Middle High German <i>man</i> ‘man’."]},{"name":"Bertran","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Jorge, Eduardo, Enrique, Joaquin, Ricardo, Aleida, Ana, Ana Maria, Elena, Felipe, Jeronimo.  French Andre.","French, Occitan, and Catalan: variant of   Bertram   or   Bertrand  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1357200,"age":83,"year":"1493","julianDay":2266368,"description":"Christopher Columbus claims Puerto Rico for Spain.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":3426319,"age":83,"year":"1493","toYear":"1898","julianDay":2266368,"description":"Spanish rule, 1493–1898","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1357201,"age":91,"year":"1501","julianDay":2269289,"description":"The Spanish Crown permitted export of slaves to America.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"UKNOWN Bertram was born in 1410, in Cayey, Puerto Rico. He had at least 1 son with Elizabeth Garner. He died in England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1410–":"1410–Surnud","1410–1440":"1410–1440","1440–